Virgil was not content with the past or present weaknesses of the particular human being called Octavian; he condemns roundly, as we have seen, the violent deeds linked with his earlier career; what Virgil extols is the vast service1 which Augustus was visibly rendering to mankind, and the still higher service which seemed to lie in the new ideal of the Empire.
